#text: Steel products company Timken Co.

warned of a second-quarter shortfall, citing a slowdown in the U.S. manufacturing industry. For the second quarter, Timken projected earnings of less than 5 cents a share with sales roughly 15 percent the same period a year earlier. Analysts polled by First Call had been expecting a profit of about 18 cents a share for the quarter. For the year, the company forecast earnings at the low end of analyst estimates of 25 cents to 95 cents a share, excluding items. The company also unveiled plans to restructure its operations to reduce costs. These plans include closing two plants, and selling a third plant, moves that will reduce its workforce by roughly 1,500. Shares closed down 37 cents to $17.29.

America Online's stock jumped 3.7 percent Monday after the
    company told money managers that advertising revenue is soaring thanks to rising

    the potential to exceed $3.1 billion this year if the Internet service provider sold out
    its ads. While only theoretical, the figure illustrates the rapidly increasing importance
    of advertising sales to the Dulles, Va.-based company. AOL, with fiscal 1997 sales
    totaling only $1.69 billion, is projected to generate about $2.51 billion in the fiscal
    year ending this June. Advertising sales reached $108.8 million last year, nearly double
    the $58.2 million of the year before. The stock closed up 4 7/16 at 123 7/8.

Headlines.Author: Frank Barnako
Headlines.Headline: Microsoft tests data delivery via TV

#text:
Microsoft
    Corp.

may find another way into the TV business, this time departing from its
    cable strategy. The company announced Tuesday it is working with 12 broadcasters and cable
    programmers in a series of nationwide trials using a portion of the television signal
    known as the vertical blanking interval to broadcast data and program enhancements into
    U.S. homes. Microsoft Windows 98 broadcast-enabled PCs will be able to receive this data.
    Broadcasters will be able to send information -- such as tickers with national news,
    sports, stocks, and headlines -- to computer users tuned to their channel. The VBI
    delivery system also allows stations to "broadcast'' data in the form of Web pages
    that can be stored on a computer hard drive and viewed later. The company said this
    capability is an immediate way to begin adding enhancements to television programs before
    digital television is introduced in the United States. Features could include Web-based
    content that is synchronized and broadcast with television programs. Among broadcasters
    participating in the test are E. W. Scripps Co., Capitol Broadcasting Co. Inc.
    and Paramount Stations Group.
